---
import DocsLayout from '../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
---

<DocsLayout title="Architecture" description="rs-grid architecture and crate structure">
  <h1>Architecture</h1>
  <p class="lead">
    rs-grid follows a unidirectional data flow. State changes propagate through
    a fixed pipeline and never travel backwards.
  </p>

  <h2>Pipeline</h2>
  <pre><code>GridState  ──►  SceneBuilder  ──►  SceneFrame  ──►  CanvasRenderer  ──►  &lt;canvas&gt;</code></pre>
  <p>
    Each step in the pipeline has a single responsibility. <code>GridState</code>
    owns the source of truth. <code>SceneBuilder</code> derives what needs to be
    drawn. <code>CanvasRenderer</code> issues draw calls. Nothing flows
    backwards.
  </p>

  <h2>GridState</h2>
  <p>
    <code>GridState</code> is the central structure. It holds three sub-states:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <code>model: GridModel</code> — column definitions and row data
    </li>
    <li>
      <code>viewport: ViewportState</code> — <code>scroll_x</code>,
      <code>scroll_y</code>, width, height
    </li>
    <li>
      <code>selection: SelectionState</code> — anchor and focus (cell, row, or
      column)
    </li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    All mutations go through <code>GridState::apply(GridCommand)</code>. Direct
    field mutation is not exposed. This makes the state easy to snapshot and
    replay.
  </p>

  <h2>Commands</h2>
  <p>
    <code>GridCommand</code> is an enum of all possible mutations. Examples:
  </p>
  <pre><code>GridCommand::ScrollTo &#123; x: f64, y: f64 &#125;
GridCommand::SelectCell &#123; row: u64, col: usize &#125;
GridCommand::Resize &#123; width: f64, height: f64 &#125;</code></pre>
  <p>
    Commands are cheap to construct and can be queued. The renderer calls
    <code>apply</code> once per animation frame with any pending commands.
  </p>

  <h2>SceneFrame</h2>
  <p>
    <code>SceneBuilder::build(&amp;grid_state)</code> returns a
    <code>SceneFrame</code> — a flat list of <code>ScenePrimitive</code> values
    that describe exactly what should appear on screen:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><code>Rect</code> — filled rectangle (cell background, selection)</li>
    <li><code>Text</code> — cell label with font, color, and clipping</li>
    <li><code>Line</code> — grid border</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    The scene is renderer-agnostic. You can implement a new backend (WebGL,
    SVG, terminal) by consuming <code>SceneFrame</code> without touching core.
  </p>

  <h2>Crate dependency graph</h2>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Crate</th><th>Depends on</th><th>WASM?</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td><code>rs-grid-core</code></td>
        <td>—</td>
        <td>No</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><code>rs-grid-scene</code></td>
        <td>core</td>
        <td>No</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><code>rs-grid-render-canvas</code></td>
        <td>scene</td>
        <td>Yes</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><code>rs-grid-web</code></td>
        <td>render-canvas</td>
        <td>Yes</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><code>rs-grid-leptos</code></td>
        <td>web</td>
        <td>Yes</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2>Adding a renderer</h2>
  <p>To add a new rendering backend:</p>
  <ol>
    <li>Create a new crate that depends on <code>rs-grid-scene</code></li>
    <li>Consume <code>SceneFrame</code> and iterate over each <code>ScenePrimitive</code></li>
    <li>Do not modify <code>rs-grid-core</code> or <code>rs-grid-scene</code></li>
  </ol>
  <div class="callout">
    <strong>Stability contract:</strong> <code>rs-grid-core</code> and
    <code>rs-grid-scene</code> have no WASM dependency. Unit tests run with
    plain <code>cargo test</code> — no browser, no Trunk, no wasm-pack.
  </div>
</DocsLayout>
